The assassination of former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri in Beirut sparked outrage and demands for justice.
Opposition leaders blamed the Lebanese and Syrian governments, calling for Syrian troops to withdraw from Lebanon.
Saudi Arabia rejected calls for an international investigation, asserting Lebanon's independence.
The bombing, claimed by a group seeking revenge, highlighted tensions in the region.
Hariri, a respected figure known for rebuilding Lebanon, was mourned by hundreds of thousands.
The funeral procession, marred by emotional outbursts, reflected a nation in mourning and turmoil.
The international community watched closely as Lebanon grappled with political upheaval and uncertainty.
